<br>
I have a horse and use it in battle all the time with my pet.<br>
<br>
Advantages of having a horse.<br>
<br>
1. Speed, if you buy an expensive one. The cheapest horse, at 8400 plat with high charisma, runs slower than jboots and takes time to get up to full speed, not good for running from a mob. The next horse cost me 25K or so (can't remember the exact price) and runs just a TAD slower than a level 51 Sow. But the most expensive one is nearly the fastest form of travel in the game, but you'll be shelling out 120K plat or so for that one.<br>
<br>
2. You med while sitting. However, you do not med while swinging any weapon. You do med while casting. If it's a spell that is longer that 6 seconds to cast will gain you back some mana in that duration. If it's a low mana cost spell like some summons (backpacks, food, water, etc.) they will seem virtually mana free to cast. (I once summoned a 10 slot backpack full on bandages for a Warrior when I was off medding and after doing that I was actually higher in mana then when I started.)<br>
<br>
3. You med while sitting and watching your pet fight or casting to back him up with blast or heal or whatever. I was doing hill giants at level 51 and my pet can solo them. But when he had two on him, all I did was cast my two heals in constant succession and the mana went down but not by much while sitting on that horse.<br>
<br>
4. Green mobs won't jump you while medding on a horse nor while changing spells in your book. Not counting green mobs that would jump you while standing, of course. <br>
<br>
5. You are medding while spinning in place, which is an average way to survey your surroundings while medding.<br>
<br>
6. Many people will come up to you and engage you in comments about your horse, and that's a plus if you're the social type.<br>
<br>
7. You're medding while banking, medding while purchasing things, medding while looting.<br>
<br>
8.  No matter how encumbered you are, you do not slow down while on a horse. I was carrying 20K to upgrade my horse, and was galloping at the same speed as if I wasn't encumbered at all.  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  However</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->,  See point 12 in disadvantages, very important side effect of this advantage.<br>
<br>
<br>
Disadvantages of owning a horse:<br>
<br>
1. Not having done actual tests, it seems to me you take much more damage from a mob's melee while on a horse. Take that with a grain of salt, since it does just seem that way.<br>
<br>
2. With my cheapest horse, it's nearly impossible to outrun a bad fighting situation. However, if you have jboots or sow on, you can just click the horse icon off and take off running as you normally do. The horse icon does not overwrite sow or jboots.<br>
<br>
3. Spinning in place (like to turn around and run) is slower on a horse.<br>
<br>
4. Moving backwards is very slow.<br>
<br>
5. You can not swim on a horse, the horse will poof if you go in deep enough water. However, they recently changed it via a patch that you can levitate a horse and run over water.<br>
<br>
6. It can be very hard to loot from up on a horse sometimes.<br>
<br>
7. It can very nearly impossible to give your pet weapons and such from up there, Fire pets for some reason seem even more difficult than others.<br>
<br>
8. You always see the back of your horses head in your view. While not a horrid thing, it can be tough when someone is at your feet asking for a DS. (or silly people asking for a sow, hehe)<br>
<br>
9. You won't fit in tight spots as you now are as tall as some of our warrior type friends.<br>
<br>
10. Can only be used outdoors.<br>
<br>
11.  Can't duck or crouch to interrupt a casting spell while on the horse, but Verant stated they are looking into this.<br>
<br>
12.  When vastly encumbered (I noticed this when I was 500 and over) going over the smallest of hills would cause me to take vasts amounts of damage.  When I was 705/86 overweight even a small hill just 2 feet high would cause me to take 300-400 points in &quot;falling&quot; damage.  Levitating myself did fix this problem.<br>
<br>
13.  Can't take my horse into freeport anymore as this photo shows:  <br>
